
[1]hyacinth

   HY'ACINTH, n. [L. hyacinthus.]

   1. In botany, a genus of plants, of several species, and a great number
   of varieties. The oriental hyacinth has a large, purplish, bulbous
   root, from which spring several narrow erect leaves; the flower stalk
   is upright and succulent, and adorned with many bell-shaped
   flowers,united in a large pyramidical spike, of different colors in the
   varieties.

   2. In mineralogy, a mineral, a variety of zircon, whose crystals,when
   distinct, have the form of a four-sided prism, terminated by four
   rhombic planes,which stand on the lateral edges. Its structure is
   foliated; its luster, strong; its fracture, conchoidal. Its prevailing
   color is a hyacinth red, in which the red is more or less tinged with
   yellow or brown. It is sometimes transparent, and sometimes only
   translucent.

   Hyacinth is a subspecies of pyramidical zircon.
